This file contains the OpenPGP public keys that Hydra release managers use to
sign release artifacts. To verify a Hydra source release, import this file and
check the detached signature (`.asc`) that ships alongside the source archive:

    # Import the project signing keys
    gpg --import KEYS

    # Verify a downloaded source archive against its signature
    gpg --verify hydra-<version>-src.tar.gz.asc hydra-<version>-src.tar.gz

A good signature from a key listed below, together with a matching SHA-512
checksum (`.sha512`), confirms the archive is an authentic, untampered release.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Release managers: append your public key to this file, never replace existing
keys (downstream users may have pinned an older key, and prior releases were
signed with it). For each key, include the human-readable `gpg --fingerprint`
block above the ASCII-armored key so a verifier can confirm the fingerprint
out of band:

    gpg --list-sigs --fingerprint <your-key-id> >> KEYS
    gpg --armor --export <your-key-id> >> KEYS

Then commit the updated KEYS file. The signing key id can be selected at
release time via the HYDRA_RELEASE_SIGNING_KEY environment variable, which
bin/prepare-release.sh passes to gpg; see docs/release-workflow.md.

